[src:great-expectations/data-validation] A table look up check compares data to a collection of allowed values.
[src:great-expectations/data-validation] Enforcement action typically rejects the data entry request and requires the input actor to make a change that brings the data into compliance.
[src:great-expectations/data-validation] This is most suitable for interactive use, where a real person is sitting on the computer and making entry.
[src:great-expectations/data-validation] It also works well for batch upload, where a file input may be rejected and a set of messages sent back to the input source for why the data is rejected.
[src:great-expectations/data-validation] Another form of enforcement action involves automatically changing the data and saving a conformant version instead of the original version.
[src:great-expectations/data-validation] This is most suitable for cosmetic change.
[src:great-expectations/data-validation] For example, converting an [all-caps] entry to a [Pascal case] entry does not need user input.
[src:great-expectations/data-validation] An inappropriate use of automatic enforcement would be in situations where the enforcement leads to loss of business information.
[src:great-expectations/data-validation] For example, saving a truncated comment if the length is longer than expected.
[src:great-expectations/data-validation] This is not typically a good thing since it may result in loss of significant data.
[src:great-expectations/data-validation] Advisory actions typically allow data to be entered unchanged but sends a message to the source actor indicating those validation issues that were encountered.
[src:great-expectations/data-validation] This is most suitable for non-interactive system, for systems where the change is not business critical, for cleansing steps of existing data and for verification steps of an entry process.
[src:great-expectations/data-validation] Verification actions are special cases of advisory actions.
[src:great-expectations/data-validation] In this case, the source actor is asked to verify that this data is what they would really want to enter, in the light of a suggestion to the contrary.
[src:great-expectations/data-validation] Here, the check step suggests an alternative (e.g., a check of a mailing address returns a different way of formatting that address or suggests a different address altogether).
[src:great-expectations/data-validation] You would want in this case, to give the user the option of accepting the recommendation or keeping their version.
[src:great-expectations/data-validation] This is not a strict validation process, by design and is useful for capturing addresses to a new location or to a location that is not yet supported by the validation databases.
[src:great-expectations/data-validation] Even in cases where data validation did not find any issues, providing a log of validations that were conducted and their results is important.
[src:great-expectations/data-validation] Failures or omissions in data validation can lead to data corruption or a security vulnerability.
[src:great-expectations/data-validation] Data validation checks that data are fit for purpose, valid, sensible, reasonable and secure before they are processed.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] A properly designed ETL system extracts data from source systems and enforces data type and data validity standards and ensures it conforms structurally to the requirements of the output.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Some ETL systems can also deliver data in a presentation-ready format so that application developers can build applications and end users can make decisions.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] The ETL process is often used in data warehousing.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] ETL systems commonly integrate data from multiple applications (systems), typically developed and supported by different vendors or hosted on separate computer hardware.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] The separate systems containing the original data are frequently managed and operated by different stakeholders.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] For example, a cost accounting system may combine data from payroll, sales, and purchasing.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] ETL and its variant ELT (extract, load, transform), are increasingly used in cloud-based data warehousing.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Applications involve not only batch processing, but also real-time streaming.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] ETL processing involves extracting the data from the source system(s).
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] In many cases, this represents the most important aspect of ETL, since extracting data correctly sets the stage for the success of subsequent processes.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Most data-warehousing projects combine data from different source systems.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Each separate system may also use a different data organization and/or format.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] The streaming of the extracted data source and loading on-the-fly to the destination database is another way of performing ETL when no intermediate data storage is required.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] An intrinsic part of the extraction involves data validation to confirm whether the data pulled from the sources has the correct/expected values in a given domain (such as a pattern/default or list of values).
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] If the data fails the validation rules, it is rejected entirely or in part.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] The rejected data is ideally reported back to the source system for further analysis to identify and to rectify incorrect records or perform data wrangling.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] In the data transformation stage, a series of rules or functions are applied to the extracted data in order to prepare it for loading into the end target.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] An important function of transformation is data cleansing, which aims to pass only "proper" data to the target.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] The challenge when different systems interact is in the relevant systems' interfacing and communicating.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Character sets that may be available in one system may not be in others.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] The load phase loads the data into the end target, which can be any data store including a simple delimited flat file or a data warehouse.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Depending on the requirements of the organization, this process varies widely.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Some data warehouses may overwrite existing information with cumulative information; updating extracted data is frequently done on a daily, weekly, or monthly basis.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Other data warehouses (or even other parts of the same data warehouse) may add new data in a historical form at regular intervals – for example, hourly.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] To understand this, consider a data warehouse that is required to maintain sales records of the last year.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] This data warehouse overwrites any data older than a year with newer data.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] However, the entry of data for any one year window is made in a historical manner.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] The timing and scope to replace or append are strategic design choices dependent on the time available and the business needs.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] More complex systems can maintain a history and audit trail of all changes to the data loaded in the data warehouse.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] As the load phase interacts with a database, the constraints defined in the database schema – as well as in triggers activated upon data load – apply (for example, uniqueness, referential integrity, mandatory fields), which also contribute to the overall data quality performance of the ETL process.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Audit reports (for example, on compliance with business rules.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Archive (Extreme, space-efficient compression for very rarely used, old data.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] ETL processes can involve considerable complexity, and significant operational problems can occur with improperly designed ETL systems.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] The range of data values or data quality in an operational system may exceed the expectations of designers at the time validation and transformation rules are specified.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Data profiling of a source during data analysis can identify the data conditions that must be managed by transform rules specifications, leading to an amendment of validation rules explicitly and implicitly implemented in the ETL process.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Data warehouses are typically assembled from a variety of data sources with different formats and purposes.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] As such, ETL is a key process to bring all the data together in a standard, homogeneous environment.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Design analysis should establish the scalability of an ETL system across the lifetime of its usage – including understanding the volumes of data that must be processed within service level agreements.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] The time available to extract from source systems may change, which may mean the same amount of data may have to be processed in less time.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Some ETL systems have to scale to process terabytes of data to update data warehouses with tens of terabytes of data.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Increasing volumes of data may require designs that can scale from daily batch to multiple-day micro batch to integration with message queues or real-time change-data-capture for continuous transformation and update.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Unique keys play an important part in all relational databases, as they tie everything together.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] A unique key is a column that identifies a given entity, whereas a foreign key is a column in another table that refers to a primary key.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Keys can comprise several columns, in which case they are composite keys.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] In many cases, the primary key is an auto-generated integer that has no meaning for the business entity being represented, but solely exists for the purpose of the relational database – commonly referred to as a surrogate key.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] As there is usually more than one data source getting loaded into the warehouse, the keys are an important concern to be addressed.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] For example: customers might be represented in several data sources, with their Social Security number as the primary key in one source, their phone number in another, and a surrogate in the third.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Yet a data warehouse may require the consolidation of all the customer information into one dimension.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] A recommended way to deal with the concern involves adding a warehouse surrogate key, which is used as a foreign key from the fact table.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Usually, updates occur to a dimension's source data, which must be reflected in the data warehouse.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] If the primary key of the source data is required for reporting, the dimension already contains that piece of information for each row.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] If the source data uses a surrogate key, the warehouse must keep track of it even though it is never used in queries or reports; it is done by creating a lookup table that contains the warehouse surrogate key and the originating key.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] This way, the dimension is not polluted with surrogates from various source systems, while the ability to update is preserved.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] The lookup table is used in different ways depending on the nature of the source data.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] A new dimension row is added with the new state of the source system, while the previous dimension row is updated to reflect it is no longer active and time of deactivation.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] ETL vendors benchmark their record-systems at multiple TB (terabytes) per hour (or ~1 GB per second) using powerful servers with multiple CPUs, multiple hard drives, multiple gigabit-network connections, and much memory.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] In real life, the slowest part of an ETL process usually occurs in the database load phase.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Databases may perform slowly because they have to take care of concurrency, integrity maintenance, and indices.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Still, even using bulk operations, database access is usually the bottleneck in the ETL process.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Whether to do certain operations in the database or outside may involve a trade-off.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] For example, removing duplicates using `distinct` may be slow in the database; thus, it makes sense to do it outside.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] On the other side, if using `distinct` significantly (x100) decreases the number of rows to be extracted, then it makes sense to remove duplications as early as possible in the database before unloading data.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] A common source of problems in ETL is a big number of dependencies among ETL jobs.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] For example, job "B" cannot start while job "A" is not finished.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] One can usually achieve better performance by visualizing all processes on a graph, and trying to reduce the graph making maximum use of parallelism, and making "chains" of consecutive processing as short as possible.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Again, partitioning of big tables and their indices can really help.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Another common issue occurs when the data are spread among several databases, and processing is done in those databases sequentially.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Sometimes database replication may be involved as a method of copying data between databases – it can significantly slow down the whole process.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] This approach allows processing to take maximum advantage of parallelism.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] For example, if you need to load data into two databases, you can run the loads in parallel (instead of loading into the first – and then replicating into the second).
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Sometimes processing must take place sequentially.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] For example, dimensional (reference) data are needed before one can get and validate the rows for main "fact" tables.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Some ETL software implementations include parallel processing.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] This enables a number of methods to improve overall performance of ETL when dealing with large volumes of data.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] All three types of parallelism usually operate combined in a single job or task.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] An additional difficulty comes with making sure that the data being uploaded is relatively consistent.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Because multiple source databases may have different update cycles (some may be updated every few minutes, while others may take days or weeks), an ETL system may be required to hold back certain data until all sources are synchronized.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Likewise, where a warehouse may have to be reconciled to the contents in a source system or with the general ledger, establishing synchronization and reconciliation points becomes necessary.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Data warehousing procedures usually subdivide a big ETL process into smaller pieces running sequentially or in parallel.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] To keep track of data flows, it makes sense to tag each data row with "row_id", and tag each piece of the process with "run_id".
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] In case of a failure, having these IDs help to roll back and rerun the failed piece.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Best practice also calls for *checkpoints*, which are states when certain phases of the process are completed.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Once at a checkpoint, it is a good idea to write everything to disk, clean out some temporary files, log the state, etc.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] An established ETL framework may improve connectivity and scalability.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] A good ETL tool must be able to communicate with the many different relational databases and read the various file formats used throughout an organization.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] ETL tools have started to migrate into enterprise application integration, or even enterprise service bus, systems that now cover much more than just the extraction, transformation, and loading of data.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Many ETL vendors now have data profiling, data quality, and metadata capabilities.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] A common use case for ETL tools include converting CSV files to formats readable by relational databases.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] A typical translation of millions of records is facilitated by ETL tools that enable users to input CSV-like data feeds/files and import them into a database with as little code as possible.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] ETL tools are typically used by a broad range of professionals – from students in computer science looking to quickly import large data sets to database architects in charge of company account management, ETL tools have become a convenient tool that can be relied on to get maximum performance.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] ETL tools in most cases contain a GUI that helps users conveniently transform data, using a visual data mapper, as opposed to writing large programs to parse files and modify data types.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] While ETL tools have traditionally been for developers and IT staff, research firm Gartner wrote that the new trend is to provide these capabilities to business users so they can themselves create connections and data integrations when needed, rather than going to the IT staff.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Gartner refers to these non-technical users as Citizen Integrators.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] In online transaction processing (OLTP) applications, changes from individual OLTP instances are detected and logged into a snapshot, or batch, of updates.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] An ETL instance can be used to periodically collect all of these batches, transform them into a common format, and load them into a data lake or warehouse.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Data virtualization can be used to advance ETL processing.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] The application of data virtualization to ETL allowed solving the most common ETL tasks of data migration and application integration for multiple dispersed data sources.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Virtual ETL operates with the abstracted representation of the objects or entities gathered from the variety of relational, semi-structured, and unstructured data sources.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] ETL tools can leverage object-oriented modeling and work with entities' representations persistently stored in a centrally located hub-and-spoke architecture.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Such a collection that contains representations of the entities or objects gathered from the data sources for ETL processing is called a metadata repository and it can reside in memory or be made persistent.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] By using a persistent metadata repository, ETL tools can transition from one-time projects to persistent middleware, performing data harmonization and data profiling consistently and in near-real time.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Extract, load, transform (ELT) is a variant of ETL where the extracted data is loaded into the target system first.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] The architecture for the analytics pipeline shall also consider where to cleanse and enrich data as well as how to conform dimensions.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Some of the benefits of an ELT process include speed and the ability to more easily handle both unstructured and structured data.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Ralph Kimball and Joe Caserta's book *The Data Warehouse ETL Toolkit*, (Wiley, 2004), which is used as a textbook for courses teaching ETL processes in data warehousing, addressed this issue.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Cloud-based data warehouses like Amazon Redshift, Google BigQuery, Microsoft Azure Synapse Analytics, and Snowflake provide highly scalable computing power.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] This lets businesses forgo preload transformations and replicate raw data into their data warehouses, where it can transform them as needed using SQL.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] After having used ELT, data may be processed further and stored in a data mart.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Most data integration tools skew towards ETL, while ELT is popular in database and data warehouse appliances.
[src:great-expectations/extract-transform-load] Similarly, it is possible to perform TEL (Transform, Extract, Load) where data is first transformed on a blockchain (as a way of recording changes to data, e.g., token burning) before extracting and loading into another data store.
